==English==
===Etymology===
{{F.}} ''[[embarrasser]]'', to block, to obstruct, from {{Sp.}} ''[[embarazer]]'', either from {{Pg.}} ''[[embaraçar]]'', from ''[[em-#Portuguese|em-]]'', from {{L.}} ''[[im-#Latin|im-]]'', in + ''[[baraça]]'', noose, rope, related to Celtic ''[[barr]]'', tuft; or from {{It.}} ''[[imbarazzare]]'', from ''[[imbarazzo]]'', obstacle, obstruction, from ''[[imbarrare]]'', to block, to bar, from ''[[im-#Italian|im-]]'', in + ''[[barra#Italian|barra]]'', bar, from Vulgar Latin ''[[barra#Vulgar Latin|barra]]'', of unknown origin
:''See [[embarrass/etymology]] for further discussion. 

===Pronunciation===
*{{audio|en-us-embarrass.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Transitive verb===
{{en-verb|embarrass|es}}

#to [[humiliate]]; to disrupt somebody's [[composure]] or [[comfort]] with acting publicly or freely; to [[disconcert]]; to [[abash]]
#:''The crowd's laughter and jeers '''embarrassed''' him.''

====Synonyms====
*(''humiliate''): [[abash]], [[discomfit]], [[disconcert]], [[humiliate]], [[shame]]

